resources.title: Dozin' with the Dinos Info Packet
resources.body: Families and group leaders, prepare for your night at the museum with this guide.

resources.title: Dinosaur Family Tree | Dinosaur Toolkit
resources.body: Examine dinosaur physical traits to identify similarities and differences in their features and construct a system of classification.

resources.title: Pump it Up | Biomechanics Toolkit
resources.body: Learn how the giraffe’s super-pump of a heart delivers blood seven feet up to the brain.

resources.title: Ancient Americas Educator Guide
resources.body: Investigate diverse cultures across different times and geographic locations in the Ancient Americas exhibition.

resources.title: Grainger Hall of Gems Educator Guide
resources.body: Explore the geological and cultural significance of a variety of gems.

resources.title: Rise of Dinosaurs | Dinosaur Toolkit
resources.body: Analyze data from a mock fossil dig to determine the differences and similarities between multiple fossil dig sites.

resources.title: Neolithic Village Flyover
resources.body: Explore a reconstruction of the Neolithic village of Szeghalom, which was located in eastern Hungary. Archaeological findings there signaled a shift from foraging to farming.

resources.title: WhyReef
resources.body: Dive into a virtual coral reef to discover marine life and connections between these sea creatures and what they eat.

resources.title: BIOlympics Game | Biomechanics Toolkit
resources.body: Jump into BIOlympics events to see how animals achieve amazing feats. Use that knowledge to choose competitors for different events.

resources.title: Artifact Observation Guide
resources.body: Encourage close examination of a single artifact—an object produced by humans—using observations and inferences.

resources.title: Specimen Observation Guide
resources.body: Encourage close examination of a single specimen—a collected example of a particular species or type—using observations and inferences.

resources.title: What Do Animals Eat? | Exploring the Field Guide
resources.body: Investigate the relationship between an animal and its environment by identifying possible food sources in each habitat.

resources.title: Families Across Place and Time | Exploring the Field Guide
resources.body: Explore similarities and differences between families across different geographic locations and time periods.

resources.title: Diversity of Life | Exploring the Field Guide
resources.body: Observe animal dioramas to compare and contrast organisms and explore the diversity of life.

resources.title: Chicago Before Skyscrapers | Exploring the Field Guide
resources.body: Observe a local ecosystem and infer how Native Americans of the Chicago region have traditionally used these resources.

resources.title: Everything Has a Purpose | Exploring the Field Guide
resources.body: Examine why plants and birds have certain features to uncover the relationship between structure and function.

resources.title: Protecting Earth's Ecosystem | Exploring the Field Guide
resources.body: Analyze methods used to address environmental issues and design strategies to protect local ecosystems.

resources.title: Exploring Cultures | Exploring the Field Guide
resources.body: Look closely at artifacts to learn how culture and geography create similarities and differences between China and Egypt.

resources.title: Hominid Adaptations | Exploring the Field Guide
resources.body: Investigate fossil remains of hominids to learn how humans and our relatives evolved over time.

resources.title: Relationships in Ecosystems | Exploring the Field Guide
resources.body: Investigate an ecosystem by observing the individual organisms as part of a larger structure—a food web.

resources.title: Conservation in Action | Exploring the Field Guide
resources.body: Examine different ways that scientists and community members conserve the environment, then analyze the results.

resources.title: Survival of the Birds | Exploring the Field Guide
resources.body: Infer whether a bird can survive in a specific environment by observing physical features such as beak, feathers, legs, and feet.

resources.title: Societies in the Ancient Americas | Exploring the Field Guide
resources.body: Observe six types of societies that developed in the Americas in response to specific environmental conditions.

resources.title: Exploring Artifacts from the Pacific | Exploring the Field Guide
resources.body: Observe and analyze artifacts from the Pacific Islands to develop evidence-based claims about how these cultures view the world.

resources.title: Plate Motion Past and Present | Dinosaur Toolkit
resources.body: Analyze and interpret data about the structures of Earth’s crust and the fossil record.

resources.title: Archaeological Footprint | China Toolkit
resources.body: Analyze how we learn about history through objects and theorize what gaps can exist in object-based stories.

resources.title: Exploring Language | China Toolkit
resources.body: Explore the history of writing in China by drawing conclusions about the impact of the written word on human civilizations and how language changes over time.

resources.title: Confucianism, Daoism, Buddhism | China Toolkit
resources.body: Explore three major belief systems in China—Buddhism, Confucianism, and Daoism—through art and artifacts.

resources.title: Maps | China Toolkit
resources.body: Analyze maps to draw conclusions about their purpose, audience, and potential bias.

resources.title: Structure and Function | China Toolkit
resources.body: Analyze early Chinese objects to understand how an object is designed or structured is related to its function.

resources.title: Exploring Objects | China Toolkit
resources.body: Analyze objects using varied lenses, including anthropology, history, economics, geography, and art history.

resources.title: Outsiders Inside | China Toolkit
resources.body: Analyze the concept of “outsiders,” or ethnic minorities, in Chinese history through artifacts and connect the concept to present experiences.

resources.title: Investigating the Qingming Scroll | China Toolkit
resources.body: Learn about the contradictions depicted in the Qingming Scroll and compare it with present-day representations of idealized societies.

resources.title: Testing the Scholars | China Toolkit
resources.body: Explore the classical Chinese civil service exam system, compare it to current exam systems, and develop a sense of what it means to be qualified for a role.

resources.title: Read, Watch, Listen, Visit: Student Resource List | China Toolkit
resources.body: Explore more ways to learn about China with your students.

resources.title: Evidence in the Unwritten | China Toolkit
resources.body: Investigate the role of an archaeologist and discover the types of questions that drive their work. Spanish subtitles available.

resources.title: Ask an Artifact | China Toolkit
resources.body: Discover what you can learn from the objects all around us when you look carefully and apply a specific disciplinary lens. Spanish subtitles available.

resources.title: Dome Strength | Biomechanics Toolkit
resources.body: Discover how much force a seemingly brittle object like an egg can withstand when it’s dome-shaped.

resources.title: Muscle Model | Biomechanics Toolkit
resources.body: Explore factors affecting muscle strength using simple models.

resources.title: Bergmann's Rule | Biomechanics Toolkit
resources.body: Uncover how an animal’s size affects its ability to regulate temperature.

resources.title: Advantages of Levers | Biomechanics Toolkit
resources.body: Test basic lever types and explore the trade-off between a force advantage and speed advantage in the animal world.

resources.title: Giraffe Heart Dissection | Biomechanics Toolkit
resources.body: Go behind the scenes in our mammals wet lab to watch the dissection of a giraffe heart.

resources.title: Thermoregulation Design Challenge | Biomechanics Toolkit
resources.body: Use animal thermoregulation as inspiration to design an eco-friendly dwelling that stays warm in the winter and/or cool in the summer.

resources.title: Locomotion Design Challenge | Biomechanics Toolkit
resources.body: Use animal movement as inspiration to design a new vehicle for traveling via land, water, and air.

resources.title: Senses Design Challenge | Biomechanics Toolkit
resources.body: Use animal senses as inspiration to design a way for humans to use their senses differently or use a new sense.

resources.title: Forces Design Challenge | Biomechanics Toolkit
resources.body: Use animal structure and function to design a way that humans can reduce the force felt and/or energy absorbed by an object.

resources.title: Island Evolution
resources.body: Discover why islands contain so many unique species.

resources.title: Mammal Phylogeny
resources.body: Discover how scientists classify the diverse mammals found on Earth.

resources.title: Being Big on Land
resources.body: Learn why being big isn’t always an advantage and find out how mythic creatures like Godzilla and King Kong could never have carried their own weight.

resources.title: The Brain Scoop: The Taxonomy of Candy
resources.body: Scientists use a system called taxonomy to group and categorize living things. What happens when you try to apply taxonomy to candy?

resources.title: The Field Revealed: Tully Monster
resources.body: Discover the Tully Monster, the state fossil of Illinois.

resources.title: The Brain Scoop: Tully Monster Mystery Solved!
resources.body: Learn how researchers discovered the Tully Monster, long believed to be an invertebrate (similar to worms), is actually a vertebrate and more closely related to fish.

resources.title: From the Field to the Field Museum
resources.body: Prepare for a field trip or object study by learning how the Field Museum collects and studies specimens and artifacts from around the world.

resources.title: Plants of the World Exhibition Guide
resources.body: Observe intricate plant models to determine the functions of their unique structures.

resources.title: Animal Survival Unit | Early Elementary Science Partnership
resources.body: Act as consultants to the City of Chicago and assess their relocation plan for urban coyotes.

resources.title: Pollination Unit | Early Elementary Science Partnership
resources.body: Interact with various models to explore the structures of plants and animals related to the process of pollination.

resources.title: Structure Function Unit | Early Elementary Science Partnership
resources.body: Design a shoe appropriate for the icy, wet, and cold conditions of Antarctica using different types of bird feet as inspiration.

resources.title: Mapping and Monarchs Unit | Early Elementary Science Partnership
resources.body: Learn how to analyze and interpret maps by studying monarch butterfly migration.

resources.title: The Night Sky Unit | Early Elementary Science Partnership
resources.body: Use night sky patterns found in folktales from around the world to explore observable patterns of the moon and stars.

resources.title: Pre-K Weather Unit | Early Elementary Science Partnership
resources.body: Observe and record weather to build a common understanding of observable weather conditions in the fall in Chicago. Then make recommendations about how SUE should prepare to play outside.

resources.title: Kindergarten Weather Unit | Early Elementary Science Partnership
resources.body: Listen to the book Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs and draw comparisons between weather forecasting and responses in Chicago and the fictional town of Chewandswallow.

resources.title: Giants from the Past | Dinosaur Toolkit
resources.body: Analyze and interpret data about sauropods and build a nonfiction narrative about how this group of dinosaurs evolved over millions of years.

resources.title: Rock Clocks Primer | Dinosaur Toolkit
resources.body: Discover how scientists determine the age of rocks and fossils and use those processes to develop a timeline of Earth's history.

resources.title: What are Fossils Primer | Dinosaur Toolkit
resources.body: Explore how fossils form and discover how scientists know where to find them.

resources.title: Who were Dinosaurs? Primer | Dinosaur Toolkit
resources.body: Uncover the features that all dinosaurs share, and determine whether a mystery species is a dinosaur.

resources.title: SUE's World | Dinosaur Toolkit
resources.body: Use fossils as clues to rebuild a North American landscape from the past and imagine the world where SUE the T. rex lived.

resources.title: Today's Dinosaurs | Dinosaur Toolkit
resources.body: Explore evidence in the physical features of living animals and dinosaur fossils to learn what living animal is most closely related to dinosaurs.

resources.title: Exhibition Investigation Guide
resources.body: Investigate a museum exhibition using the claim, evidence, reasoning cycle.

resources.title: Members' Nights Guide
resources.body: See what you can explore behind the scenes during our annual Members' Nights.

resources.title: Mission to the Mesozoic

resources.body: Craft the perfect field trip to the museum for your students.

resources.body: Get the details for your group as they explore the museum.

resources.body: Learn how the first giant dinosaurs like Glacialisaurus moved by exploring this 3D model.

resources.body: Read The Legend of the Parákata or color your own version of the story!

resources.title: Monarch Habitat Guide
resources.body: Identify the plants that welcome monarchs, as well as the butterfly’s different life stages.
